`IFormFile` buffers the entire request body in memory — that's why it OOMs. Instead, read the raw multipart stream section-by-section and write each chunk directly to disk.

**Key changes:**

1. **Disable the default form body-size limit** and read from `HttpRequest.Body` via `MultipartReader`.
2. **Stream each section to a `FileStream`** so only a small buffer is ever in memory.
3. **Configure Kestrel's max request body size** to allow 2 GB.

```csharp
// Program.cs
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.Features;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities;
using Microsoft.Net.Http.Headers;

var builder = WebApplication.CreateBuilder(args);

// Allow up to 2 GB request bodies in Kestrel
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(o =>
    o.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024);

var app = builder.Build();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpContext ctx) =>
{
    var contentType = ctx.Request.ContentType ?? "";
    var boundary = HeaderUtilities.RemoveQuotes(
        MediaTypeHeaderValue.Parse(contentType).Boundary).Value;

    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Missing multipart boundary.");

    // Disable the default form value/body limits for this request
    var formFeature = ctx.Features.Get<IFormFeature>();
    ctx.Features.Set<IFormFeature>(null);

    var reader = new MultipartReader(boundary, ctx.Request.Body);
    var section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();

    while (section is not null)
    {
        if (ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(
                section.ContentDisposition, out var cd)
            && cd.DispositionType.Equals("form-data")
            && !string.IsNullOrEmpty(cd.FileName.Value))
        {
            // Sanitise the file name
            var fileName = Path.GetFileName(cd.FileName.Value);
            var savePath = Path.Combine("/tmp/uploads", fileName);

            Directory.CreateDirectory("/tmp/uploads");

            await using var fs = new FileStream(
                savePath, FileMode.Create, FileAccess.Write,
                FileShare.None, bufferSize: 81920);

            // Streams chunk-by-chunk — only 80 KB in memory at a time
            await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);
        }

        section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();
    }

    return Results.Ok("Upload complete.");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();               // no antiforgery token for API uploads

app.Run();
```

**Why this works:**

| Concern | Solution |
|---|---|
| `IFormFile` buffers everything | `MultipartReader` streams section-by-section |
| Kestrel rejects bodies > 30 MB | `MaxRequestBodySize = 2GB` lifts the cap |
| `CopyToAsync` memory use | Only the 80 KB `bufferSize` is allocated |

**If you're behind a reverse proxy** (IIS / Nginx), raise its limit too:

- **IIS** — add `<requestLimits maxAllowedContentLength="2147483648" />` in `web.config`.
- **Nginx** — set `client_max_body_size 2g;`.
